Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, total they reach 29 percent
A noticeable weakening of both parties of the previous grand coalition and a clear strengthening of the right-wing populist parties brought after the first preliminary results the early parliamentary elections of Sunday in Austria.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly severe losses, where the position of the former chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously on the tip.
In contrast, the election leader of the alliance prepares for the future of Austria (BZÖ), the Carinthian state governor Jörg Haider, for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest force in the country with 29.8 percent of the votes, compared to the last elections in 2006 it loses 5.5 percent of the votes.
The ÖVP cut even worse, losing almost nine percent of the votes with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in the Austrian post-war history, and especially of the People's Party, which had demanded the early elections, this is a truly catastrophic result.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a clear advantage over the SPÖ.
But voters probably punished the party for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results there were speculations about a possible resignation of the party chairman and former vice chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could be the case already on Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party bureau.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the electoral debacle, i.e. to a renewal of the grand coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP.
In view of the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Liberals (FPÖ) received 18 percent, while the BZÖ eleven percent of the votes - the Social Democrats expressed their fears that 1999 could be repeated when the People's Party and the Populists agreed (then the FPÖ was still uniform, in 2005 it split from the BZÖ) on a joint government, which had even caused sanctions on the part of the European Union.
Jörg Haider, who has already stated that he is willing to cooperate with each party, is obviously relying on this development and expects a return to Vienna to Austria's federal policy.
In addition, the Green Party moved into parliament, which suffered slight losses and slipped from third to fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably mastered the four percent hurdle and therefore did not enter parliament.
