Turkey broadens the diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, the European powers were interested in penetrating deep into Turkey's hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps within Asia, stands one of the finest relics of this failed, imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha station was designed by the two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the guides tell you.
The building sits riding at the end of the platforms with a tower at each corner of the front and thus looks like some provincial German town hall.
The rock is dirty.
The whole building decays about
But once you're inside the vaulted ticket counter, there's no doubt about the grandeur of the project, whose most western access this was.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Bagdad Society.
Germany, which was a late migrant in the imperialist game, had to implement its ambitions to dominate the Middle East by means of a train connection to Damascus, Baghdad, and further beyond what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperialist plans were faltering during the First World War.
His railroad tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabs.
The relative isolation from its surrounding region, generated by the insurmountable borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
British forces moved out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies from Palestine and Syria
And there was also bad news for the Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, a munitions train flew into the air, destroying the artful roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly disintegrated, far from history.
Today, however, this railway line, at least symbolically, serves as a gateway to Anatolia and everything east of it to highlight the expansion of the diplomatic horizon of Turkey.
The ruling judicial and development party, the AKP, has introduced a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the neighbouring regions, generated by the borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
Now there is a policy of rapprochement.
Remarkably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iran and Iraq and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to assess the key figures of this new foreign policy, I went on the night train to the Turkish capital Ankara to visit one of the leading foreign policy experts of the AKP, Turkish MEP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a bumpy journey on tracks that produced the same step of the old world in the well-known documentary "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is regarded as a new city, for the new secular state plan to turn back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity
This has caused some mistrust in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to the AKP's main office, a specially designed ultra-modern stone and steel structure, in a developing suburb surrounded by semi-finished shopping malls and pubs where middle managers met in suits, both men and women, to complete the first business of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even packed a Blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey with its immediate neighbours.
The Cold War was an exceptional phenomenon," he tells me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
Today, it has to look east and west at the same time.
There wouldn't be either one or the other.
She'd have to do both.
"But surely Turkey could eventually," I asked, "must be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he said, "did not want to have to face this decision."
He then pointed out a point that almost everyone I talked to here said almost routinely: Turkey's relations, not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, are just as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be that, in the figurative sense, Europe as a whole can travel on the same rail tracks eastward towards Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha's station, after another largely sleepless night, I thought of these two German lords, Mr. Ritter and Mr. Conu, who had watched this building build 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East could now, to a large extent, lie in Turkey's hands.
And when I was waiting at the dock for the ferry that was supposed to take me back over the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe" in those days.
At the time, at least, there did not seem to be much doubt as to which continent should have a claim to this fascinating country.
