'Car Bee' that avoids collisions
In order to advance the development of the technologies for accident prevention, Nissan was inspired by nature this time, to be precise, by the bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight goes back to the swarm behavior of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C and represents the first step in the technologies for accident prevention.
The engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Technical Development Center have developed this small robot in cooperation with Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the renowned University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Head of Technology-PR and R&D-Brand Management, the BR23C represents an extension of the four-layer Nissan security shield.
This robot is designed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds its own oval-shaped flight room, which is very similar to the Nissan security shield.
But the most important are the bee's faceted eyes, which can see in all directions over an angle of 300 degrees, which allows her to fly undisturbed in her personal airspace without interruption.
In order to recreate the all-round perspective, the technicians developed the so-called Laser Range Finder (LRF).
He notices obstacles located in front of the BR23C at a distance of up to two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an in-vehicle microprocessor, which is directly translated into signal to avoid collision
`At the moment when obstacle is noticed, the small robot will imitate the bee flight and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at 90o or even larger angles to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference to any other system is that this evasive maneuver is absolutely instinctive.
If not, the robot could not be able to react with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles,' explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the senior engineer of this project.
In contrast to a bee, the robot can neither deviate upwards or downwards, but it can also not exceed; it can move only on two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in the infinite directions and in the infinite way that the bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used the rotation function in addition to acceleration and braking functions, so that the small robot avoids collisions.
`This device only takes a few seconds to process the information and act according to this information.
It does not require neither the information nor the intuitive logic of the maneuvers carried out, so it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of storage space.
That sounds surprising, but it's not about the GBs and not even about the MBs of the storage space.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan predicts to introduce in series cars over the next ten years.
The robot works with lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than a variety of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite in order to lead to the destination while driving, avoiding the obstacles on the way.
