Morgan Stanley provides her capital to MUFG
Morgan Stanley announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG) into its company, which would be the first bank in Japan to spend nine billion dollars and thus take over 21% of its capital, an innovation due to a strong fall in its stock market price.
One week after a preliminary agreement was made public, the two banks stated that MUFG will buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley common shares at a uniform price of 25.25 dollars, which amounts to a total of three billion dollars.
The price assumed is less than 19% of the share price of August 31st.
MUFG will invest an additional six billion dollars in the acquisition of convertible shares that will secure a profit of 10% and can be re-sold at a price of 31,25 dollars.
Morgan Stanley stated that the global business will be conducted on the basis of a uniform average price of $29, i.e. 28% above the current price.
However, the Morgan Stanley share dropped by 6.79% to $23.07 at 17.00 GMT.
‘This strategic link is an important opportunity to accelerate the transition from Morgan Stanley to the status of a holding bank,' said John Mack, Director General of the American Group.
Morgan Stanley accepted this status last week, which is supposed to allow him to extend their business to new areas, but under the supervision of the Federal Reserve.
Their association with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces Wall Street's biggest names to take a much more cautious stance than before.
The modalities presented on Monday also show that the agreement has been changed over the last few days: Last Monday, Morgan had simply declared that she would sell up to 20% of her shares to Japan for about $8.5 billion.
‘A week ago', Toshihide Mizuno, Managing Director of MUFG, said in Tokyo, ‘we thought that the stake would consist entirely of common shares.
But given the current economic and market situation, we wanted to reduce the risks and secure ourselves. '
Based on a balanced average price, MUFG will pay 7% below their price for their Morgan Stanley shares.
And the business will go with a reduction in earnings of about 20% per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferential shares into common shares in one year if the latter are exchanged at more than 50% above the value of the sale, i.e. at approximately 47 dollars, within a given period.
Morgan Stanley assures that the funds provided by MUFG will enable him to exploit investment opportunities, strengthen their balance sheet and increase their sales.
However, a press spokesman from the group refused to provide more detailed information on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After the investment of MUFG, Morgan Stanley should be able to record a solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in this sector.
Morgan explained that since the end of August he had 'significantly' lowered his balance sheet.
The last few weeks have been hard for the group that had to watch their stock market price decline by half, while the price of insurance against insolvency has increased.
This price fell on Monday, but remained at a high level, at around 12%.
Goldman Sachs, the only other 'survivors' of the major investment banks on Wall Street after the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the purchase of Merrill Lynch, announced last week that he had withdrawn $15 billion, partly from Berkshire Hathaway, the group of Warren Buffett.
Rafael Correa this Monday in Quito.
Refound the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of the Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, the Bolivian Evo Morales and the Equatorian Rafael Correa.
It was that third person who, this Sunday, following the example of his like-minded and friends, put the plan of a new constitution for election.
Mission accomplished, because according to the public results, which amounted to 80% of the vote, 64% voted 'yes' in the referendum.
According to these results, 28% voted 'no', 7% voted 'no', and 0.7% were cast blank.
In order for the constitutional project to be adopted, more than half of the votes cast must be cast.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the polling stations' exits and a census of a non-governmental organization had announced a clear victory for 'yes', prophesying to him 63% to 70%.
On the night of Sunday to Monday, by the way, Rafael Correa had demanded the victory of his constitutional project.
The 'constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly', he had assured in Guayaquil, the seat of the government 280 kilometers southwest of Quito, and congratulated the Equatorians.
Of course Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales, but also by his Chilean like-minded Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which was held silently according to the observational delegation of the Organization of the American States (OAS), referred to a text consisting of 444 points to secure the 'new socialism' for which the President is committed.
The constitutional project transfers the power of the state to the economy by giving it the sole right to 'development planning' in a country that largely lives from oil production by foreign companies and from foreign currencies that send emigrants to the country.
The project, which is being promoted by the Correa elected in 2006, also grants the Head of State greater power, which will be able to exercise up to two consecutive mandates of four years each, and will have the opportunity to dissolve the National Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will make use of this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also secures the principle of free medical care and education, which the President has already begun to introduce in this country with 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population live below the poverty line.
In the end, it also envisages banning the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington to use an Equatorial base as a base for American antidrug operations.
The 19 hostages were freed in Chad
An Egyptian command started the attack on the abductors of the eleven tourists and their eight companions who had been captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions, who were held in the desert for eleven days, were brought back to the Egyptian capital in a healthy and unscathed manner this Monday afternoon.
In the morning they had been liberated from an Egyptian command in Chad.
Apparently in good condition, the hostages reached the al-Maza military base right next to Cairo International Airport at around 3.30 p.m. on board a special aircraft.
They were taken directly, without being able to talk to the press, aboard a helicopter to the hospital of Maadi, a foreigner district of Cairo, to be examined there.
They all enjoy 'best health' and the hijackers 'were not paid a ransom', said the Egyptian Minister of Tourism Zoheir Garanna on the runway.
After being captured on September 19 in an off-road safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border area of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, the group of hostages was repeatedly taken from one hiding place by 35 unknown kidnappers.
They are eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and also eight Egyptians: two leaders, four chauffeurs, a border guard and the director of the Agency Egyptus, organiser of the safari.
An Egyptian security officer said that 30 members of the Special Forces launched the attack at night, just before dawn, on board two helicopters.
'On both sides, shots were fired and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled,' said this person in charge, who wants to remain anonymous.
He explained that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian Special Forces had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commands.
The head of the Italian diplomat Franco Frattini reported from Belgrade where he is, on the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
'We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men from the intelligence service and special forces,' he explained without further details.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
The night before, the Sudanese army had claimed to have stopped an off-road vehicle in a patrol, where the kidnappers were, six of whom were killed, including Chad's leader, and two arrests.
The army declared that they were connected to a rebel group from Darfur, the Libération du Soudan-Unité (SLA-U), which, however, immediately denied the movement.
Letters - The silent majority of culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes headlines and is central to the current election campaign.
All the better.
But one area of our cultural life remains in oblivion.
Who will stand up and denounce the pitiful sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical sites that are starving to death?
What politician will dare to remind the federal government that it neglects its monuments and its culturally important buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, there are no proper laws that effectively protect our cultural heritage?
Did you know that the French government is making 3.5 million euros available solely for the restoration of Chinon Castle in the Loire Valley?
With our American neighbours, the Constitution of their country states that the protection of cultural heritage belongs to the American culture, and that this cultural heritage must be protected by all citizens, by all Members of Parliament and by all government districts, in mutual agreement.
In Quebec, in the Association of Quebec Historical Societies, at least 40,000 volunteers gathered in 211 historical societies are trying to deal intensively with history, to save the numerous private archives with a few dime, and to preserve the archaeological remains.
They are also often the watchdogs of our cultural heritage, who protest with the power of despair when promoters and decision-makers release their bulldozers on our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When will there be a stage for history and cultural heritage?
Benelux governments national parts of Fortis Bank
With a partial nationalization, the Benelux states want to use the Belgian-Dutch Fortis Bank, which has been turbulenced by the US financial crisis, to help: The three states make a total of EUR 11.2 billion available to the bank and insurance institution, which also has branches in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands consulted at the highest level on the weekend, together with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commissioner of the European Commission's Competition Authority.
In the eurozone, Fortis is the first victim of the international financial market crisis that has been going on for a year, so decisions that are now being taken in connection with the bank could be a precedent.
In line with the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states buy the respective shares of the bank at around 49 percent.
The bank will probably sell some of its holdings, especially the insurance activities purchased by the Dutch ABN Amro last year.
The shares of Fortis started a steep descent last week, and serious crisis scenarios were already emerging in the second half of the week.
However, analysts agree that the bank, with its 85,000 employees, is far too large for a bankruptcy.
The institution's securities fell by 12% to a 14-year low on Friday.
Since January, the value of the shares has decreased by more than two thirds.
In view of the current share prices, the Group's market value is EUR 14 billion, which, according to the management, is unrealistic.
According to the management, the USD 700 billion US bailout package and the resulting uncertainty on the markets are responsible for the downfall of Fortis shares.
On Monday, however, prices rose slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed new Director General of the Bank.
The financial institution was also looking for a private buyer, but no interested party with a factual offer was found.
However, the Belgian government was trying to calm down - no investor should trembl for his money, it was said.
There has been no panic among the customers so far, the branches of the bank have not been stormed.
In Hungary the Fortis has independent branches, but it also calls leasing companies its own.
Fox in the henhouse
Because of a person's drug use, life and health insurance companies in America often refuse to enter into a contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programs that in any case link the use of the drug data to the consent of the person concerned.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we entrust the fox to the chickens" - quoted the Washington Post Richard Dick, developer of the program for tracking prescription data.
Insurances determine the fees as well as the payment amounts in case of damage depending on the health condition of the customer, and if the risk is overestimated, the insurance will not be taken out at all.
In the past, the customer was sent to a medical examination and the contract was concluded only in the knowledge of the results of the examination.
Ten years ago Dick invented a much cheaper method: Based on the customer's identification number, he obtains the data from the pharmacies for the last one and a half years, i.e., which products were purchased, and the program calculates from what illness the customer suffers and what his health condition is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering medication, it could be concluded that his blood fat level is untreatable, which would automatically lead him to a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so that insurance only has to do the paperwork more, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the disadvantages is that many drugs can be taken for various purposes, such as migraines and hot flushes, but also against depression.
The latter is, from the insurer's point of view, a high risk factor, while the latter is not.
For the query and processing of the data, own societies have formed, which, before receiving the data, ask the patient for his consent.
In the meantime, they have to do so by law, although omissions have not yet been punished.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory tests and combine them with the data on drug use. Thus, they provide an even more accurate picture of the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to the data and control of their use becomes more difficult at the same time.
Although there is a separate law on data protection for health data, its effect is limited to health service providers and insurance companies.
The bill has already been submitted to Congress, according to which the authorities could also control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard realizes that this is too little, so he wants to further develop his program so that the data can only be passed on with the consent of the person concerned.
Another question, of course, is that the person concerned can hardly prohibit access to his data, as the insurance companies otherwise do not enter into a contract with him.
And so the chickens are somehow left to the fox's mercy.
Global menu from Marseille
European Union and India double trade
After the European Union and India are both leading trading partners of each other, this was the main topic among other global problems at the ninth summit.
The Franco-Indian summit is also taking place today, where the main subject of discussion is cooperation in the nuclear sector.
While the European Union acknowledges that India is an emerging, democratic great power that should be given more voice and voice on international issues, the member states have not yet been able to agree on whether or not to support the permanent membership of New Delhi in the UN Security Council.
This question was not discussed at yesterday's ninth summit in Marseille.
French President and current EU President Nicolas Sarkozy, Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Chief Diplomat Javier Solana received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh. An agreement was reached to double trade over the next five years, i.e. increase it to a good 100 billion euros.
Given that trade in goods had increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this target is not even so ambitious.
In this sense, the 26 existing civil aviation agreements with India have also been legally merged into an agreement so that air transport will also be encouraged in the future.
India wants to sign the Free Trade Agreement with the Union by 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the pact.
The aim was to achieve a balance in the current imbalance between the EU and India: while the Union is the number one partner in India, New Delhi is only ninth among the EU partners.
The summit was dedicated to global concerns.
Among them was the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, or terrorism, which both sides strongly condemned, and the convening of a UN conference was also perpetrated.
The Doha Round should also be concluded, with both sides to blame for failure.
The EU stressed that it adheres to its energy and climate programme, i.e. that pollutant emissions are to be reduced by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agreed with this, as did the proposal to reach a kind of global compromise at the upcoming climate summit and to reduce greenhouse gas production by 50 percent by 2050.
The rise in food prices should also be combated, so both support the convening of an international conference on the financial crisis.
The Indian head of government is visiting the French capital today, where he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
In Paris, however, contracts to French companies worth EUR 20 billion for the construction of nuclear reactors in India are expected.
According to the Agency reports, the agreement is to be adopted for 15 years.
Over 300 Italian publishers in Frankfurt
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the International Frankfurt Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishers will be present at the 60th Book Fair, the most important international event for the acquisition of rights.
For the current event, the international Frankfurt Book Fair expects more than 7,000 exhibitors from 101 countries. They will spread over 17,790 square meters of the fair and present more than 403,000 titles. Turkey will be the guest of honour of the event.
The Undersecretary for the Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Cultural Activities Maria Giro will represent the Italian government during the opening ceremony in the exhibition hall: Italy will be represented in the 264 sqm exhibition space "Punto Italia".
This will be followed by a press conference near the room structure in the exhibition hall 5.0 of the book fair: on this occasion, figures, trends and perspectives around publishing in Italy will be discussed.
According to the data, the importance of foreign writers' books is decreasing throughout, but especially in the adult and youth sectors.
The billionaire Steve Fossett's small plane disappeared a year ago
The small plane of Steve Fossett, who disappeared on a flight over the Nevada desert on September 3, 2007, was found.
The items have been found on a plateau of 3000 m above sea level, in the Sierra Nevada Mammoth Lakes area between the states of California and Nevada.
However, no human remains were found inside the aircraft.
The sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, completely disenchanted the last doubts during a press conference: "The plane has been located and a force has been sent out to do so. Now we have the certainty that it is the plane with which Steve Fossett flew on the day of his disappearance."
Mr. Anderson also confirmed that no human remains were found on or near the plane.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Department of Traffic Safety (Ntsb) noted that just a few hours after the aircraft was sighted, a crew was sent out to identify the aircraft: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, which was lost on September 3, 2007, after Fossett started a 3-hour flight in Yerington, Nevada.
Yesterday, in California, near the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal belongings were found by a couple near their home on Mammoth Lakes.
These are two ID cards called Fossetts, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of illinois, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett had been abandoned one month after its disappearance.
The billionaire had gained a place in history through a long series of records.
In 2002, in his sixth attempt, he was the first person to orbit the world ball in a hot air balloon: a two-week, lonely flight.
Three years later, he flew around the world in a single flight without a stopover with an airplane.
Among his several records also counts a height flight of 15445 m over the Andes, however, this with a co-pilot.
Glk, the advertising you don't expect
A Suv that falls out of the conventional schemes due to its original design and special lines, the expansive surface and its clear angles.
Mercedes-Benz has tried with this offroader to breathe new breath into the sector.
Due to its exceptional characteristics, the Suv Glk will also be unconventional, which will be on display in the Mercedes-Benz showroom from 17 October.
Thus, the advertising drum that will accompany the appearance of the new model will also appear in a new dress, namely in the form of a 3D campaign – a novelty in the car sector in backward Italy.
A project with a maximum effort, to be carried out in various lanes, which will occupy the central shopping mile of Milan, the Corso Como, until 15 November.
The first fase will consist of the presentation of the car in shape, whereby 3D glasses, which are distributed near the Corso Como, will give the whole a special look: the new Suv will thus appear in its almost real dimensions as a three-dimensional model.
In fact, the car will appear so seemingly from the poster on which it is depicted.
With the help of the Elumina8 technology, the new Glk will be illuminated at different moments in all its details in order to reassemble as a whole.
Without a doubt, it is Mercedes' concern with this advertisement to introduce a new type of autoreclame into this rather stereotyped field.
But will it succeed in stimulating the interest of future buyers? We will see it.
